## Phase 1 — Receiving & Evaluating the Animation

1. Received 480 PNG frames from Marwan Hasnaoui (pixel art animation of Holdt at a typewriter by a fire in the rain)
2. Evaluated file properties:
   - Format: PNG (Deflated compression)
   - Resolution: 1920x1080
   - File size: ~233KB per frame (216KB compressed)
   - Naming convention: Sequential integers — 1.png through 480.png
   - Delivery folder: animation/
   - Confirmed in Figma: 1920x1080 native resolution
3. Removed a stray pane file from the folder to ensure clean export readiness

---

## Phase 2 — First Pass in DaVinci Resolve (Round 1)

4. Opened DaVinci Resolve Pro for the first time (no prior experience)
5. Imported the 480 PNGs as an image sequence into the Media Pool — DaVinci treats sequentially numbered PNGs as a single clip
6. Original clip properties: 19 seconds at 24fps (480 frames / 24fps = ~20s)
7. Set playback speed to 50% using the duration/speed controls
8. Exported as MP4 → result: ~40 seconds at 12fps
9. Used FFmpeg to merge the Resolve-exported MP4 with LofiLoop.wav (Carson Thatcher's original 1h40m lo-fi composition) into a single combined file

---

## Phase 3 — Second Pass with FFmpeg (Round 2)

The pivot: Woke up the next day and the animation still felt too fast at 12fps. Went back into DaVinci Resolve to evaluate different speeds, decided another 50% reduction was correct → target: 6fps.

10. Decided to skip Resolve for this pass and go directly to FFmpeg, pulling from the original PNG folder at 6fps for a cleaner result with no intermediate export
11. Source files moved to SanDisk Extreme 2TB SSD at D:\StreamSourceFiles\ — portable, device-agnostic (same path works from White Plains or Athens)
12. Built the 6fps silent video directly from PNGs:

```
ffmpeg -framerate 6 -i "D:\StreamSourceFiles\HoldtAnimationPNGs1\%d.png" -c:v libx264 -pix_fmt yuv420p "D:\StreamSourceFiles\holdt_6fps.mp4"
```

13. Looped the animation to match the full 1h40m music duration (6000 seconds):

```
ffmpeg -stream_loop -1 -i "D:\StreamSourceFiles\holdt_6fps.mp4" -i "D:\StreamSourceFiles\LofiLoop.wav" -map 0:v -map 1:a -c:v libx264 -c:a aac -t 6000 "D:\StreamSourceFiles\HoldtLoop.mp4"
```

Command breakdown:
- -framerate 6 — sets input frame rate to 6fps when reading PNGs
- %d.png — tells FFmpeg to read sequentially numbered files (1.png, 2.png, etc.)
- -c:v libx264 -pix_fmt yuv420p — H.264 encoding, standard color format for compatibility
- -stream_loop -1 — loops the video input infinitely until -t duration is reached
- -map 0:v -map 1:a — takes video from first input, audio from second input
- -c:a aac — AAC audio encoding (required for MP4 container)
- -t 6000 — total output duration in seconds (6000s = 1h40m, matching the music loop)

14. Final output: HoldtLoop.mp4
   - Size: 1.28GB
   - Duration: 1 hour 40 minutes
   - Video: H.264, 1920x1080, 6fps, ~1710 Kbps
   - Audio: AAC, 48000 Hz, stereo, ~129 Kbps
   - Total bitrate: ~1843 Kbps

15. Loaded into OBS → LoFiRadio scene as a Media Source → Loop enabled. Running at 0.8% CPU. Confirmed: looks and sounds exactly right.

---

## Phase 4 — Architecture Decision: VPS vs. OBS-Always-On

The question considered: Should the lo-fi radio stream from the laptop via OBS running 24/7, or from a VPS running independently?

Two options evaluated:

Option A — OBS always-on: OBS streams continuously to Restream. Going live = switch a scene. Going back to lo-fi = switch back. No server needed. Fully seamless. Requires laptop to stay on and OBS running at all times.

Option B — VPS as primary broadcaster: A cloud server runs FFmpeg indefinitely. Going live requires stopping the VPS stream, starting OBS, then reversing afterward. Causes a brief YouTube blip on each handoff. Laptop can be off. Server costs $6/month.

Decision: VPS as primary broadcaster (Option B). Reasoning: the goal was to have the stream survive laptop downtime. VPS gives full independence — the inn stays open whether or not the laptop is on.

A second architecture discussion happened later the same day: After the handoff workflow was built and tested, Evan was asked about his actual laptop habits. He said the laptop is always on when streaming. The question was re-evaluated with a ranked priority list: Simple (1) > Automated (2) > Seamless (3) > Branded (4). Given those priorities, OBS-always-on was identified as the cleaner long-term architecture — but the VPS was already live, tested, and working. Decision: keep VPS as current setup and revisit this architecture upgrade later.

The seamless handoff question: Evan asked if there was a way to eliminate the YouTube blip entirely during handoffs. The answer: yes — a traffic controller layer (e.g., nginx-rtmp on the server) could sit between both sources and YouTube, switching instantly without a disconnect. Decision: deferred to a future session.

