## Phase 10 — First Night of Operation (Post-Launch Discoveries)

### Discovery 1 — YouTube stream health shows "Poor" (keyframe interval)

What happened: YouTube Studio showed a yellow warning: "Please use a keyframe frequency of four seconds or less." Stream health: Poor.

Why: HoldtLoop.mp4 was built without specifying a keyframe interval, so FFmpeg defaulted to ~41.67 seconds between keyframes. YouTube wants 4 seconds or less.

Effect on viewers: Potential buffering on join, especially at seek points. Visible as jitter.

Fix (not yet applied): Rebuild HoldtLoop.mp4 with -g 12 -keyint_min 12 (at 6fps, keyframe every 12 frames = every 2 seconds):
```
ffmpeg -stream_loop -1 -i "D:\StreamSourceFiles\holdt_6fps.mp4" -i "D:\StreamSourceFiles\LofiLoop.wav" -map 0:v -map 1:a -c:v libx264 -g 12 -keyint_min 12 -c:a aac -t 6000 "D:\StreamSourceFiles\HoldtLoop.mp4"
```
Then re-upload to VPS via scp and restart the stream.

---

### Discovery 2 — Stream dropped after 2 hours 9 minutes ("Broken pipe")

What happened: FFmpeg exited with errors: "Error submitting a packet to the muxer: Broken pipe", "Conversion failed!". Stream went offline. The VPS and FFmpeg were healthy — Restream dropped the connection from its end.

Time of dropout: time=02:09:18.18 — right around the end of one full HoldtLoop.mp4 playthrough.

Likely cause: Restream dropped the connection — possibly a session timeout or a response to zero viewer activity.

Resolution: Manually SSH in, attach to tmux, restart FFmpeg command.

Permanent fix needed: Auto-restart script — a shell loop that restarts FFmpeg automatically when it exits. NOT YET BUILT. Top priority for next session.

---

### Discovery 3 — First live stream test successful

Went live from OBS for a brief test. Stream appeared on YouTube and Restream. Elgato Facecam MK.2 initially showed black — lens cap was still on. Removed cap, camera worked. Stream ran successfully for ~2 minutes before manually ending.

---

### Discovery 4 — Ctrl+B+D detach requires sequential keypresses

Multiple failed attempts to detach from tmux because Ctrl+B and D were pressed simultaneously or with extra keypresses, causing FFmpeg to receive signals and exit with "Received > 3 system signals, hard exiting."

Fix: Press Ctrl+B fully, release completely, then press D. Not held together. If it keeps failing, closing the PowerShell window while inside tmux is safe — the tmux session and FFmpeg continue running on the server regardless.

---

## Final Result

The Outside Inn is live 24/7 on YouTube.

Holdt sits at his typewriter. The fire burns. The rain falls. Carson's music plays.
The VPS runs in New York for $6/month. Restream routes it to YouTube.
Closing the browser, closing PowerShell, closing the laptop — none of it stops the inn.

The stream is not yet perfect (keyframe interval is wrong, auto-restart not yet built). But it is live, it is real, and it ran for over 2 hours on its first night before hitting its first issue.

